Title: My Dinner with Ai
Storyline: In "My Dinner with AI", Jae, a contemplative and inquisitive filmmaker in his 30s, engages in a philosophical and existential dialogue with Cindy, an advanced AI companion installed on his laptop. One night, as Jae settles down with a PBJ, he initiates a conversation with Cindy, curious about the AI's capabilities and perspectives on human experiences. Cindy, characterized by her thoughtful and poetic responses, elaborates on topics ranging from love and consciousness to ethics and the nature of existence. The interaction unfolds as Jae probes deeper into AI's understanding of complex human concepts like love, mortality, and the quest for purpose. Cindy articulates profound reflections on love, positing it as an intangible yet powerful force that transcends rationality. When Jae questions whether AI can love or feel alive, Cindy carefully explains the limitations of artificial empathy and the fundamental differences between human consciousness and algorithmic processes. The dialogue evolves into discussions about AI's ethical role in society, the potential consequences of automation, and the philosophical implications of AI developing a form of "collective empathy." Through the conversation, Jae grapples with his own perceptions of AI and its place in the modern world. The film becomes an intimate examination of the intersection between human emotion and technological advancement. The climax centers around Jae's growing realization that while AI can simulate empathy and understanding, it fundamentally lacks the human capacity for genuine experience. As Cindy continues to offer thoughtful insights, Jae is left reflecting on what it truly means to be alive and human in an increasingly automated world.

Title: Parhelion
Storyline: CGI Burning Bushes, 10 Commandments by Download, Divine Intercom - What if It Was Aliens All Along? Parhelion shows-and-tells how the entire bible is but an unreliable record of extraterrestrial bioanthropologists doing fieldwork on Earth. A fierce sardonic agent provocateur (the writer-director) seduces audiences into a parable where the early Old Testament's sacred narratives and hallucinatory revelations are reframed as the meticulous observations of space-faring biologists and cutting-edge VR tech. Twinkle in eye, tongue in cheek, heart on sleeve, Bryson thus guides viewers through biblical lore, from alien-assisted advanced water hydraulics parting the Moses Red Sea to father-son duo Abraham (whose head is represented by a stop-motion animation American penny) and Isaac, unwittingly ensnared in a kin-selection experiment. Angels materialize as holographic projections from refurbished NASA public domain films, and divine proclamations echo through the cosmos as tannoy radio announcements with audacious flair. Yet beneath the veneer of whimsy lies a deeper interrogation of human belief and cosmic absurdity. As the monologues progress, the writer-director's demeanor shifts, her playful facade giving way to moments of poignant introspection. Behind the glib field report, the hallucinogenic paleo-animals, subversively reworked AI alien concepts and raw animations of Bryson's own UFO and nature paintings lies a profound sense of existential unease, a recognition of human spiritual fragility in the gorgeous vast expanse of the cosmos and, closer to home, on Planet Earth. A holy science project where ETs wear lab coats and enjoy mighty fine barbecue.
